<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
     PANEL 4 — PRS
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<div class="panel" id="panel-5" data-panel-idx="5">
  <p class="section-intro">The Product Requirements Specification captures <strong style="color:#f7fafc">what the system must do</strong> at the top level — measurable, customer-facing, technology-agnostic. Each requirement gets a unique ID from birth and immediately opens a row in the RTM skeleton.</p>

  <!-- SMART criteria -->
  <div class="grid3" style="margin-bottom:20px">
    <div class="box" style="border-top:3px solid #3182ce">
      <div style="font-family:'DM Mono',monospace;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;color:#63b3ed;margin-bottom:6px">S — Specific</div>
      <p style="font-size:12px;color:#a0aec0;line-height:1.6">States exactly what is required. No weasel words: "adequate", "sufficient", "user-friendly" are not requirements.</p>
      <div class="amber-alert" style="margin-top:10px;padding:8px">
        <span style="font-size:11px;color:#fbd38d">✗ "The trailer shall be aerodynamic"</span><br>
        <span style="font-size:11px;color:#68d391">✓ "Drag coefficient Cd ≤ 0.28 at 65 mph"</span>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="box" style="border-top:3px solid #3182ce">
      <div style="font-family:'DM Mono',monospace;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;color:#63b3ed;margin-bottom:6px">M — Measurable</div>
      <p style="font-size:12px;color:#a0aec0;line-height:1.6">Has a numeric threshold with units. If you cannot state a pass/fail criterion, it is not a requirement — it is a design intent.</p>
      <div class="amber-alert" style="margin-top:10px;padding:8px">
        <span style="font-size:11px;color:#fbd38d">✗ "Long battery life"</span><br>
        <span style="font-size:11px;color:#68d391">✓ "≥ 150 mi range at 65 mph, 70°F"</span>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="box" style="border-top:3px solid #3182ce">
      <div style="font-family:'DM Mono',monospace;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;color:#63b3ed;margin-bottom:6px">T — Testable</div>
      <p style="font-size:12px;color:#a0aec0;line-height:1.6">A test can be written for it today — before the design exists. If you cannot describe a test method, the requirement is not ready.</p>
      <div class="amber-alert" style="margin-top:10px;padding:8px">
        <span style="font-size:11px;color:#fbd38d">✗ "Customers shall love the HMI"</span><br>
        <span style="font-size:11px;color:#68d391">✓ "SUS score ≥ 75 with n=8 users"</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- PRS examples -->
  <div class="box">
    <div class="eyebrow-sm">Lightship L1 — PRS sample (system-level)</div>
    <div id="prs-list"><!-- injected --></div>
  </div>

  <div class="grid2 mt20">
    <div class="box">
      <div class="eyebrow-sm">Why PRS comes after WBS</div>
      <p style="font-size:13px;color:#cbd5e0;line-height:1.75">PRS requirements are technology-agnostic and architecture-agnostic at system level — but you still need to know <em>what system you are building</em> before you can write a meaningful PRS. "Range ≥ 150 mi" only makes sense once you've committed to an EV powertrain architecture. The WBS confirms the architecture boundaries that bound the system.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="box">
      <div class="eyebrow-sm">RTM skeleton opens at PRS</div>
      <p style="font-size:13px;color:#cbd5e0;line-height:1.75">The moment the first PRS requirement is written, its ID goes into the RTM with status <span class="rtm-status status-open">OPEN</span>. There is no "write the RTM at V&V" — by that point you have lost the ability to prove that every requirement has a test.</p>
      <div class="amber-alert mt12">
        <strong style="color:#f6ad55">Common failure mode: </strong>
        <span style="font-size:12px;color:#fbd38d">Teams that start the RTM at V&V consistently find 15–30% of requirements with no corresponding test case, and 10–20% of test cases with no corresponding requirement.</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="center">
    <button class="btn btn-amber" onclick="showPanel(5)">Next: FRS — Allocate to Subsystems →</button>
  </div>
</div>


<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
     PANEL 5 — FRS
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<div class="panel" id="panel-6" data-panel-idx="6">
  <p class="section-intro">The Functional Requirements Specification <strong style="color:#f7fafc">decomposes PRS requirements into subsystem behaviours</strong>. Each FRS requirement is owned by exactly one WBS control account — which is why the WBS must exist before the FRS is written.</p>

  <!-- Allocation diagram -->
  <div class="box" style="margin-bottom:20px">
    <div class="eyebrow-sm">Requirement allocation — PRS → FRS → CA owner</div>
    <div id="allocation-diagram"><!-- injected --></div>
  </div>

  <div class="grid2">
    <div class="box">
      <div class="eyebrow-sm">FRS sample — CA-A: Aero/Structure</div>
      <div id="frs-aero"><!-- injected --></div>
    </div>
    <div class="box">
      <div class="eyebrow-sm">FRS sample — CA-B: Power System</div>
      <div id="frs-power"><!-- injected --></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="grid2 mt20">
    <div class="insight" style="max-width:none">
      <div class="label">WHY FRS CANNOT PRECEDE WBS</div>
      <p>FRS requirements are allocated to subsystems. If the WBS doesn't exist, the subsystem names don't exist. You end up writing FRS requirements to vague functional areas, then having to re-allocate them when the WBS is finally drawn — guaranteed rework.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="insight" style="max-width:none;border-color:#b7791f">
      <div class="label" style="color:#f6ad55">INTERFACE CONTROL DOCUMENTS</div>
      <p>FRS writing surfaces every interface between CAs — and each interface needs a formal ICD. The FRS and ICDs are written in parallel: as each cross-CA requirement is written, the ICD register gains a new entry. By CDR, every ICD must be at Maturity Level 2 (draft agreed).</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="center">
    <button class="btn btn-blue" onclick="showPanel(6)">Next: RTM — Traceability Matrix →</button>
  </div>
</div>


<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
     PANEL 6 — RTM
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<div class="panel" id="panel-7" data-panel-idx="7">
  <p class="section-intro">The RTM is not a document written at V&V — it is a <strong style="color:#f7fafc">living register that grows from the first PRS requirement through to final test closure</strong>. It is the only artefact that proves every requirement has a test and every test has a requirement.</p>

