<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
     PANEL 7 — BUDGET ESTIMATING
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<div class="panel" id="panel-8" data-panel-idx="8">
  <p class="section-intro">Budget is estimated bottom-up from the WBS: tasks → work packages → control accounts → programme total. The WBS is the only structure that makes a bottom-up estimate possible — without it, you are guessing at a programme level with no way to reconcile the number against actual scope.</p>

  <!-- Method selector -->
  <div style="display:flex;gap:10px;margin-bottom:20px;flex-wrap:wrap" id="budget-method-tabs">
    <button class="btn btn-sm btn-blue" onclick="setBudgetView('bottomup')" id="bm-bottomup">Bottom-Up Estimate</button>
    <button class="btn btn-sm" style="background:#2d3748;color:#a0aec0" onclick="setBudgetView('analogical')" id="bm-analogical">Analogical / Parametric</button>
    <button class="btn btn-sm" style="background:#2d3748;color:#a0aec0" onclick="setBudgetView('contingency')" id="bm-contingency">Contingency &amp; Reserve</button>
    <button class="btn btn-sm" style="background:#2d3748;color:#a0aec0" onclick="setBudgetView('earned')" id="bm-earned">Earned Value (EVM)</button>
  </div>

  <div id="budget-view-bottomup">
    <div class="grid2" style="margin-bottom:18px">
      <div class="box">
        <div class="eyebrow-sm">How bottom-up estimating works</div>
        <div style="font-size:12px;color:#cbd5e0;line-height:1.75">
          <div style="display:flex;gap:8px;margin-bottom:10px;align-items:flex-start"><span class="step-counter" style="background:#3182ce">1</span><span><strong style="color:#f7fafc">Task-level estimate:</strong> Each task owner estimates labour hours (best / most-likely / worst) and material costs. Three-point estimate reduces individual bias.</span></div>
          <div style="display:flex;gap:8px;margin-bottom:10px;align-items:flex-start"><span class="step-counter" style="background:#dd6b20">2</span><span><strong style="color:#f7fafc">Roll up to WP:</strong> Sum all task estimates within the WP. Add WP-level risk reserve (typically 10–15% for well-understood WPs).</span></div>
          <div style="display:flex;gap:8px;margin-bottom:10px;align-items:flex-start"><span class="step-counter" style="background:#9f7aea">3</span><span><strong style="color:#f7fafc">Roll up to CA:</strong> Sum WPs within the control account. CA manager owns the CA budget — this is the cost baseline unit.</span></div>
          <div style="display:flex;gap:8px;align-items:flex-start"><span class="step-counter" style="background:#2f855a">4</span><span><strong style="color:#f7fafc">Programme total:</strong> Sum all CAs + management reserve + programme-level contingency. Submitted to board at Gate 1.</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="box">
        <div class="eyebrow-sm">Three-point task estimating (PERT)</div>
        <div style="background:#1a202c;border-radius:8px;padding:14px;margin-bottom:12px">
          <div style="font-family:'DM Mono',monospace;font-size:11px;color:#63b3ed;margin-bottom:8px">Formula: Expected = (O + 4M + P) ÷ 6</div>
          <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr 1fr;gap:8px;text-align:center;margin-bottom:10px">
            <div style="background:#1c4532;border:1px solid #276749;border-radius:5px;padding:8px"><div style="font-size:10px;color:#718096">Optimistic (O)</div><div style="font-family:'DM Mono',monospace;font-size:14px;color:#68d391;font-weight:700">$8K</div></div>
            <div style="background:#2d2007;border:1px solid #b7791f;border-radius:5px;padding:8px"><div style="font-size:10px;color:#718096">Most Likely (M)</div><div style="font-family:'DM Mono',monospace;font-size:14px;color:#f6ad55;font-weight:700">$12K</div></div>
            <div style="background:#742a2a;border:1px solid #c53030;border-radius:5px;padding:8px"><div style="font-size:10px;color:#718096">Pessimistic (P)</div><div style="font-family:'DM Mono',monospace;font-size:14px;color:#fc8181;font-weight:700">$22K</div></div>
          </div>
          <div style="background:#2d3748;border-radius:5px;padding:8px;text-align:center">
            <span style="font-size:10px;color:#718096">Expected cost: </span>
            <span style="font-family:'DM Mono',monospace;font-size:15px;color:#f7fafc;font-weight:700">$13.0K</span>
            <span style="font-size:10px;color:#718096"> &nbsp;|&nbsp; Std Dev: </span>
            <span style="font-family:'DM Mono',monospace;font-size:13px;color:#a0aec0">$2.3K</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p style="font-size:11px;color:#a0aec0;line-height:1.6">The pessimistic estimate is typically 2–3× the optimistic for hardware NPI — never average O and P. Skewing the formula toward the most-likely case (×4 weight) reflects that most tasks land near the centre of the range, not the extremes.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Budget roll-up table -->
    <div class="box" style="padding:0;overflow:hidden;margin-bottom:18px">
      <div style="background:#1a202c;padding:12px 18px;border-bottom:1px solid #2d3748">
        <div class="eyebrow-sm" style="margin-bottom:0">Lightship L1 — bottom-up budget roll-up</div>
      </div>
      <div style="overflow-x:auto">
        <table style="width:100%;border-collapse:collapse;font-size:12px">
          <thead>
            <tr style="background:#1e293b">
              <th style="padding:10px 14px;text-align:left;font-family:'DM Mono',monospace;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;color:#718096;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:.08em;border-bottom:1px solid #4a5568">Control Account</th>
              <th style="padding:10px 14px;text-align:right;font-family:'DM Mono',monospace;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;color:#718096;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:.08em;border-bottom:1px solid #4a5568">Labour</th>
              <th style="padding:10px 14px;text-align:right;font-family:'DM Mono',monospace;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;color:#718096;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:.08em;border-bottom:1px solid #4a5568">Materials</th>
              <th style="padding:10px 14px;text-align:right;font-family:'DM Mono',monospace;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;color:#718096;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:.08em;border-bottom:1px solid #4a5568">Tooling</th>
              <th style="padding:10px 14px;text-align:right;font-family:'DM Mono',monospace;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;color:#718096;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:.08em;border-bottom:1px solid #4a5568">Testing</th>
              <th style="padding:10px 14px;text-align:right;font-family:'DM Mono',monospace;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;color:#718096;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:.08em;border-bottom:1px solid #4a5568">WP Reserve</th>
              <th style="padding:10px 14px;text-align:right;font-family:'DM Mono',monospace;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;color:#63b3ed;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:.08em;border-bottom:1px solid #4a5568">CA Total</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody id="budget-rollup-tbody"></tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="grid2">
      <div class="box" style="border-top:3px solid #63b3ed">
        <div class="eyebrow-sm">Cost categories defined</div>
        <div style="font-size:12px;color:#cbd5e0;line-height:1.8">
          <div><strong style="color:#f7fafc">Labour</strong> — Engineering hours × fully-loaded rate ($150–$220/hr NRE). Largest category in development.</div>
          <div style="margin-top:6px"><strong style="color:#f7fafc">Materials</strong> — Prototype parts, raw materials, purchased components (cells, electronics). Priced from should-cost model.</div>
          <div style="margin-top:6px"><strong style="color:#f7fafc">Tooling</strong> — Moulds, fixtures, test rigs. One-time NRE spend; amortised separately from recurring unit cost.</div>
          <div style="margin-top:6px"><strong style="color:#f7fafc">Testing</strong> — Lab fees, wind tunnel time, regulatory submission fees, certification costs.</div>
          <div style="margin-top:6px"><strong style="color:#f7fafc">WP Reserve</strong> — 10–20% buffer held by CA manager for known unknowns within each WP.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="box" style="border-top:3px solid #f6ad55">
        <div class="eyebrow-sm">Why the WBS makes this possible</div>
        <p style="font-size:12px;color:#cbd5e0;line-height:1.75">Without the WBS you have no list of tasks to estimate. Without task estimates you have no WP estimate. Without WP estimates you cannot build a CA budget. Without CA budgets the programme total is a guess — and a guess cannot be defended to a board or tracked during execution.</p>
        <div class="amber-alert" style="margin-top:10px;padding:10px">
          <strong style="color:#f6ad55;font-size:11px">Top-down vs bottom-up: </strong>
          <span style="font-size:11px;color:#fbd38d">Top-down estimates (analogical) are useful early for feasibility checks but are typically ±40–50%. Bottom-up estimates from a complete WBS narrow to ±15–20%. Both are needed — use top-down at Gate 0, bottom-up at Gate 2 when the WBS is complete.</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div id="budget-view-analogical" style="display:none">
    <div class="grid2" style="margin-bottom:18px">
      <div class="box">
        <div class="eyebrow-sm">Analogical estimating</div>
        <p style="font-size:13px;color:#cbd5e0;line-height:1.75;margin-bottom:12px">Use data from a previous similar programme and scale by size/complexity. Best used at Gate 0 when the WBS doesn't yet exist.</p>
        <div style="background:#1a202c;border-radius:8px;padding:14px;font-size:12px">
          <div style="font-family:'DM Mono',monospace;font-size:10px;color:#718096;margin-bottom:8px;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:.1em">Example: Lightship L1 analogical estimate</div>
          <div style="display:flex;justify-content:space-between;padding:6px 0;border-bottom:1px solid #2d3748"><span style="color:#a0aec0">Reference programme (Airstream carbon concept)</span><span style="font-family:'DM Mono',monospace;color:#f7fafc">$9.2M NRE</span></div>
          <div style="display:flex;justify-content:space-between;padding:6px 0;border-bottom:1px solid #2d3748"><span style="color:#a0aec0">Scale factor: +EV powertrain complexity</span><span style="font-family:'DM Mono',monospace;color:#f6ad55">×1.6</span></div>
          <div style="display:flex;justify-content:space-between;padding:6px 0;border-bottom:1px solid #2d3748"><span style="color:#a0aec0">Scale factor: −chassis (no custom chassis)</span><span style="font-family:'DM Mono',monospace;color:#68d391">×0.85</span></div>
          <div style="display:flex;justify-content:space-between;padding:6px 0;border-bottom:1px solid #2d3748"><span style="color:#a0aec0">Scale factor: +regulatory (new LFP cert)</span><span style="font-family:'DM Mono',monospace;color:#f6ad55">×1.12</span></div>
          <div style="display:flex;justify-content:space-between;padding:8px 0;margin-top:4px"><span style="color:#f7fafc;font-weight:600">Analogical estimate</span><span style="font-family:'DM Mono',monospace;color:#63b3ed;font-weight:700;font-size:14px">~$14.0M</span></div>
          <div style="font-size:10px;color:#4a5568;margin-top:4px;font-style:italic">Accuracy: ±40%. Compare to bottom-up at Gate 2: $13.3M total. Analogical within 5% here — rare in practice.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="box">
        <div class="eyebrow-sm">Parametric estimating</div>
        <p style="font-size:13px;color:#cbd5e0;line-height:1.75;margin-bottom:12px">Use statistical relationships between cost and measurable parameters. Common in aerospace; applicable to EV hardware.</p>
        <div style="background:#1a202c;border-radius:8px;padding:14px;font-size:12px">
          <div style="font-family:'DM Mono',monospace;font-size:10px;color:#718096;margin-bottom:8px;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:.1em">Common cost estimating relationships (CERs)</div>
          <div style="margin-bottom:8px;padding:8px;background:#2d3748;border-radius:5px">
            <div style="font-family:'DM Mono',monospace;color:#63b3ed;font-size:11px;margin-bottom:3px">Battery pack NRE cost</div>
            <div style="font-family:'DM Mono',monospace;color:#f7fafc;font-size:12px">≈ $85K × (kWh usable)^0.72</div>
            <div style="font-size:10px;color:#718096;margin-top:3px">For 75 kWh: ≈ $2.4M NRE (aligns with CA-B estimate)</div>
          </div>
          <div style="margin-bottom:8px;padding:8px;background:#2d3748;border-radius:5px">
            <div style="font-family:'DM Mono',monospace;color:#dd6b20;font-size:11px;margin-bottom:3px">Composite tooling cost</div>
            <div style="font-family:'DM Mono',monospace;color:#f7fafc;font-size:12px">≈ $1,400 × (surface area m²)^1.15</div>
            <div style="font-size:10px;color:#718096;margin-top:3px">For 18 m² aeroshell: ≈ $320K tooling</div>
          </div>
          <div style="padding:8px;background:#2d3748;border-radius:5px">
            <div style="font-family:'DM Mono',monospace;color:#9f7aea;font-size:11px;margin-bottom:3px">Firmware NRE (lines of code)</div>
            <div style="font-family:'DM Mono',monospace;color:#f7fafc;font-size:12px">≈ $35–$55 per SLOC (safety-grade)</div>
            <div style="font-size:10px;color:#718096;margin-top:3px">For 40K SLOC: $1.4M–$2.2M (CA-D range)</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="insight" style="max-width:none">
      <div class="label">WHEN TO USE WHICH METHOD</div>
      <p>Gate 0: analogical only (WBS doesn't exist). Gate 1: parametric CERs for major subsystems. Gate 2: bottom-up from complete WBS. All three methods should agree within ±20% at Gate 2 — if they don't, the WBS or scope definition has an error.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div id="budget-view-contingency" style="display:none">
    <div class="grid2" style="margin-bottom:18px">
      <div class="box">
        <div class="eyebrow-sm">Contingency vs management reserve — they are not the same</div>
        <div style="font-size:12px;color:#cbd5e0;line-height:1.8">
          <div style="background:#1a202c;border-radius:8px;padding:14px;margin-bottom:12px">
            <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr;gap:12px">
              <div>
                <div style="font-family:'DM Mono',monospace;font-size:10px;color:#f6ad55;font-weight:700;margin-bottom:6px;text-transform:uppercase">Contingency Reserve</div>
                <div style="font-size:11px;color:#a0aec0;line-height:1.6">For <strong style="color:#f7fafc">known unknowns</strong> — risks you have identified but not fully quantified. Held at CA level. CA manager can release without programme approval. Sized from risk register: Σ(probability × impact) per risk item.</div>
              </div>
              <div>
                <div style="font-family:'DM Mono',monospace;font-size:10px;color:#fc8181;font-weight:700;margin-bottom:6px;text-transform:uppercase">Management Reserve</div>
                <div style="font-size:11px;color:#a0aec0;line-height:1.6">For <strong style="color:#f7fafc">unknown unknowns</strong> — risks you haven't identified. Held at programme level. Requires programme manager approval to release. Typically 10–15% of total authorised budget.</div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div style="display:flex;gap:8px;align-items:flex-start;margin-bottom:8px"><span style="color:#4a5568;flex-shrink:0">▸</span><span>You must never use management reserve to cover a known risk — that is a symptom of under-costed contingency.</span></div>
          <div style="display:flex;gap:8px;align-items:flex-start"><span style="color:#4a5568;flex-shrink:0">▸</span><span>If contingency is consistently zero at programme close, you over-budgeted. If it is consistently exhausted by Gate 3, your risk register is incomplete.</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="box">
