<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
     PANEL 8 — CRITICAL PATH
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<div class="panel" id="panel-9" data-panel-idx="9">
  <p class="section-intro">The critical path is the longest sequence of dependent tasks from programme start to each gate. Any task on the critical path has zero float — one day of slip on a critical task is one day of slip on the gate date. <strong style="color:#f7fafc">Tracking it is not a one-time calculation; it must be updated every two weeks as actuals replace estimates.</strong></p>

  <!-- Sub-tab selector -->
  <div style="display:flex;gap:10px;margin-bottom:20px;flex-wrap:wrap">
    <button class="btn btn-sm btn-blue" onclick="setCPView('network')" id="cp-network">Network Diagram</button>
    <button class="btn btn-sm" style="background:#2d3748;color:#a0aec0" onclick="setCPView('float')" id="cp-float">Float &amp; Slack</button>
    <button class="btn btn-sm" style="background:#2d3748;color:#a0aec0" onclick="setCPView('tracking')" id="cp-tracking">Tracking Protocol</button>
    <button class="btn btn-sm" style="background:#2d3748;color:#a0aec0" onclick="setCPView('compression')" id="cp-compression">Schedule Compression</button>
  </div>

  <div id="cp-view-network">
    <p style="font-size:13px;color:#a0aec0;margin-bottom:16px;line-height:1.65">The network diagram shows task dependencies. The critical path (red) is the path with the longest total duration — all tasks on it have zero float. Near-critical paths (amber) have float of ≤ 10 days and must be watched closely.</p>
    <div class="box" style="padding:20px;margin-bottom:18px">
      <div class="eyebrow-sm">Lightship L1 — Critical Path to Gate 3 (CDR)</div>
      <div id="cp-network-diagram"></div>
    </div>
    <div class="grid2">
      <div class="box">
        <div class="eyebrow-sm">How the critical path is calculated (CPM)</div>
        <div style="font-size:12px;color:#cbd5e0;line-height:1.8">
          <div style="display:flex;gap:8px;margin-bottom:8px;align-items:flex-start"><span class="step-counter">1</span><span><strong style="color:#f7fafc">Forward pass:</strong> Calculate the Earliest Start (ES) and Earliest Finish (EF) for every task, working left to right through the network.</span></div>
          <div style="display:flex;gap:8px;margin-bottom:8px;align-items:flex-start"><span class="step-counter">2</span><span><strong style="color:#f7fafc">Backward pass:</strong> Fix the project end date and work right to left, calculating Latest Start (LS) and Latest Finish (LF) for every task.</span></div>
          <div style="display:flex;gap:8px;margin-bottom:8px;align-items:flex-start"><span class="step-counter">3</span><span><strong style="color:#f7fafc">Float calculation:</strong> Float = LS − ES = LF − EF. Zero float = critical. Negative float = already late.</span></div>
          <div style="display:flex;gap:8px;align-items:flex-start"><span class="step-counter">4</span><span><strong style="color:#f7fafc">Identify path:</strong> Trace the chain of zero-float tasks from start to end — this is the critical path.</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="box">
        <div class="eyebrow-sm">Critical vs near-critical — Lightship L1 (Gate 3)</div>
        <div id="cp-path-list"></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div id="cp-view-float" style="display:none">
    <div class="grid2" style="margin-bottom:18px">
      <div class="box">
        <div class="eyebrow-sm">Total float vs free float</div>
        <div style="font-size:12px;color:#cbd5e0;line-height:1.8;margin-bottom:12px">
          <div style="background:#1a202c;border-radius:8px;padding:12px;margin-bottom:10px">
            <div style="font-family:'DM Mono',monospace;font-size:10px;color:#63b3ed;margin-bottom:6px">TOTAL FLOAT</div>
            <div>How much a task can slip before delaying the gate date. Shared among all tasks in the path — using it on one task removes it from all downstream tasks on the same path.</div>
          </div>
          <div style="background:#1a202c;border-radius:8px;padding:12px">
            <div style="font-family:'DM Mono',monospace;font-size:10px;color:#9f7aea;margin-bottom:6px">FREE FLOAT</div>
            <div>How much a task can slip before delaying its immediate successor only. A task can have free float = 0 and total float > 0 — it cannot slip without impacting the next task, but the next task has slack before the gate.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="amber-alert" style="padding:10px">
          <strong style="color:#f6ad55;font-size:11px">The sharing problem: </strong>
          <span style="font-size:11px;color:#fbd38d">If a path has 20 days of total float and 5 tasks share it, each task manager thinks they have 20 days. If the first task uses all 20 days, the remaining 4 tasks have zero — and their owners don't know it. Float must be managed centrally by the programme manager, not distributed.</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="box">
        <div class="eyebrow-sm">Float table — Lightship L1 WPs to Gate 3</div>
        <div id="float-table"></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div id="cp-view-tracking" style="display:none">
    <div class="grid2" style="margin-bottom:18px">
      <div class="box">
        <div class="eyebrow-sm">Bi-weekly critical path update protocol</div>
        <div style="font-size:12px;color:#cbd5e0;line-height:1.8">
          <div style="display:flex;gap:8px;margin-bottom:10px;align-items:flex-start"><span class="step-counter">1</span><span><strong style="color:#f7fafc">Task status update:</strong> Each task owner reports actual % complete (by task closure, not gut feel) every two weeks in the programme scheduler (MS Project / Primavera / Jira).</span></div>
          <div style="display:flex;gap:8px;margin-bottom:10px;align-items:flex-start"><span class="step-counter">2</span><span><strong style="color:#f7fafc">Recalculate:</strong> Scheduler recalculates all ES/EF/LS/LF based on actuals. Critical path may shift — a task that had 5 days of float may now have 0.</span></div>
          <div style="display:flex;gap:8px;margin-bottom:10px;align-items:flex-start"><span class="step-counter">3</span><span><strong style="color:#f7fafc">Near-critical alert:</strong> Any task with float ≤ 10 days is escalated to the programme manager. Tasks with float ≤ 5 days go to weekly review.</span></div>
          <div style="display:flex;gap:8px;margin-bottom:10px;align-items:flex-start"><span class="step-counter">4</span><span><strong style="color:#f7fafc">Gate forecast update:</strong> Update the predicted gate date based on the revised critical path. If gate slip is projected, trigger a compression analysis immediately — not when the gate arrives.</span></div>
          <div style="display:flex;gap:8px;align-items:flex-start"><span class="step-counter">5</span><span><strong style="color:#f7fafc">Publish schedule health:</strong> Issue a two-page schedule health report: current critical path, top-3 float risks, gate forecast vs baseline, and any compression actions approved.</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="box">
        <div class="eyebrow-sm">Schedule health dashboard — Week 56 (Gate 3 forecast)</div>
        <div id="schedule-health"></div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="box">
      <div class="eyebrow-sm">Red flags that indicate critical path has been lost</div>
      <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr;gap:12px;font-size:12px;color:#cbd5e0;line-height:1.6">
        <div style="display:flex;gap:8px;align-items:flex-start"><span style="color:#fc8181;flex-shrink:0;font-size:14px">⚠</span><span><strong style="color:#fc8181">Baseline schedule unchanged</strong> for 4+ weeks while actuals slip — someone is hiding the critical path update.</span></div>
        <div style="display:flex;gap:8px;align-items:flex-start"><span style="color:#fc8181;flex-shrink:0;font-size:14px">⚠</span><span><strong style="color:#fc8181">All tasks reported 90% complete</strong> for two or more reporting cycles — percent complete is not being measured by task closure.</span></div>
        <div style="display:flex;gap:8px;align-items:flex-start"><span style="color:#f6ad55;flex-shrink:0;font-size:14px">⚠</span><span><strong style="color:#f6ad55">Float consumed faster than schedule advances</strong> — the programme is burning its buffer without recovering schedule.</span></div>
        <div style="display:flex;gap:8px;align-items:flex-start"><span style="color:#f6ad55;flex-shrink:0;font-size:14px">⚠</span><span><strong style="color:#f6ad55">Multiple near-critical paths simultaneously</strong> — when 3+ paths have ≤ 10 days float, the programme has no recovery slack left.</span></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div id="cp-view-compression" style="display:none">
    <p style="font-size:13px;color:#a0aec0;margin-bottom:16px;line-height:1.65">When the critical path is longer than the target gate date, you have two legitimate tools: crashing (add resources to critical tasks) and fast-tracking (run critical tasks in parallel). Both have costs and risks that must be explicitly traded.</p>
    <div class="grid2" style="margin-bottom:18px">
      <div class="box" style="border-top:3px solid #3182ce">
        <div class="eyebrow-sm" style="color:#63b3ed">Crashing — add resources to critical tasks</div>
        <p style="font-size:12px;color:#cbd5e0;line-height:1.65;margin-bottom:12px">Add people, equipment, or overtime to compress a critical task's duration. Cost goes up; risk stays the same. Always crash the cheapest critical task first.</p>
        <div style="background:#1a202c;border-radius:8px;padding:12px;font-size:11px">
          <div style="font-family:'DM Mono',monospace;font-size:10px;color:#718096;margin-bottom:8px;text-transform:uppercase">Crash cost analysis — Gate 3 slip recovery</div>
          <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:2fr 1fr 1fr 1fr;gap:4px;font-family:'DM Mono',monospace;font-size:10px;margin-bottom:6px;color:#718096">
            <div>Task</div><div style="text-align:right">Normal dur.</div><div style="text-align:right">Crash dur.</div><div style="text-align:right">Cost/week</div>
          </div>
          <div style="border-top:1px solid #2d3748;padding-top:6px">
            <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:2fr 1fr 1fr 1fr;gap:4px;padding:4px 0;border-bottom:1px solid #2d3748"><span style="color:#cbd5e0">Wind tunnel model fab</span><span style="text-align:right;color:#a0aec0">4 wks</span><span style="text-align:right;color:#68d391">2.5 wks</span><span style="text-align:right;color:#f6ad55">+$18K/wk</span></div>
            <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:2fr 1fr 1fr 1fr;gap:4px;padding:4px 0;border-bottom:1px solid #2d3748"><span style="color:#cbd5e0">BMS PCB fab + assembly</span><span style="text-align:right;color:#a0aec0">3 wks</span><span style="text-align:right;color:#68d391">2 wks</span><span style="text-align:right;color:#f6ad55">+$12K/wk</span></div>
            <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:2fr 1fr 1fr 1fr;gap:4px;padding:4px 0;border-bottom:1px solid #2d3748"><span style="color:#cbd5e0">CNC mould machining</span><span style="text-align:right;color:#a0aec0">6 wks</span><span style="text-align:right;color:#fc8181">4 wks</span><span style="text-align:right;color:#fc8181">+$45K/wk</span></div>
            <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:2fr 1fr 1fr 1fr;gap:4px;padding:6px 0;margin-top:4px"><span style="color:#f7fafc;font-weight:600">Optimal crash: WT + BMS</span><span></span><span style="text-align:right;color:#68d391;font-weight:700">2.5 wks saved</span><span style="text-align:right;color:#f6ad55;font-weight:700">+$45K</span></div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="box" style="border-top:3px solid #9f7aea">
        <div class="eyebrow-sm" style="color:#b794f4">Fast-tracking — run tasks in parallel</div>
        <p style="font-size:12px;color:#cbd5e0;line-height:1.65;margin-bottom:12px">Start a successor task before its predecessor is fully complete. No added cost; higher rework risk. Only works where the dependency is a partial handoff, not a full deliverable.</p>
        <div style="background:#1a202c;border-radius:8px;padding:12px;font-size:11px">
          <div style="font-family:'DM Mono',monospace;font-size:10px;color:#718096;margin-bottom:8px;text-transform:uppercase">Fast-track opportunities — Gate 3</div>
          <div style="margin-bottom:10px;padding:8px;background:#2d3748;border-radius:5px">
            <div style="color:#b794f4;font-weight:600;margin-bottom:3px">✓ Safe to fast-track</div>
            <div style="color:#a0aec0">Start BMS PCB layout (1.2.2.2) at 70% of schematic completion (1.2.2.1). Saves 1 week. Risk: 20% chance of 2-day rework if schematic changes.</div>
          </div>
          <div style="margin-bottom:10px;padding:8px;background:#2d3748;border-radius:5px">
            <div style="color:#b794f4;font-weight:600;margin-bottom:3px">✓ Safe to fast-track</div>
            <div style="color:#a0aec0">Begin FW thermal PID development (1.4.2.3) against preliminary BMS data while cell characterisation (1.2.1.2) completes. Saves 2 weeks with minor retune risk.</div>
          </div>
          <div style="padding:8px;background:#2d3748;border-radius:5px">
            <div style="color:#fc8181;font-weight:600;margin-bottom:3px">✗ Unsafe to fast-track</div>
            <div style="color:#a0aec0">Cannot start CNC mould machining before OML freeze. Zero partial-handoff possible — moulds cut to wrong surface = 100% scrap.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="insight" style="max-width:none">
      <div class="label">THE COMPRESSION DECISION HIERARCHY</div>
      <p>First exhaust fast-tracking opportunities on low-risk task pairs — zero cost. Then crash the cheapest critical tasks first (lowest cost/week saved). Only then consider scope reduction (removing features to hit the gate). Scope reduction requires a formal ECR and stakeholder sign-off — it is not a unilateral PM decision.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

